******
[2] Saudi Arabia, Jeddah total 11 cases including 2 deaths
Date: Tue 8 Apr 2014
Source: Saudi Arabia Ministry of Health [in Arabic, mach. trans., edited]
http://www.moh.gov.sa/CoronaNew/PressReleases/Pages/mediastatemenet-2014-04-08-001.aspx


Press release regarding the validity of Jeddah [MERS-CoV reports]
-----------------------------------------------------------------
Further to the press releases issued on the status of the coronavirus in Jeddah province, the Directorate of Health Affairs in Jeddah would like to reassure everyone that the health situation [with respect to the MERS-CoV situation in Jeddah] is stable and there is full coordination between all the sectors concerned and the continuous follow up of His Highness the Emir of Makkah Region and HH Governor of Jeddah and the Minister of Health, where work continues on the epidemiological investigation and all precautionary measures to deal with the virus have been taken. To ease the pressure on King Fahad General Hospital, emergency cases (Red Crescent) were referred to other hospitals for 24 hours only, providing an opportunity to take action cleansing the emergency department according to [established norms].

Since the 1st case of MERS-CoV infection in Jeddah, immediately upon receipt of notification of the suspicion of the 1st case in a nurse at King Abdul Aziz [Hospital], precautionary measures were taken according to the plan prepared for them, and are as follows:
- laboratory confirmation of MERS-CoV infection in a male nurse;
- activation of a MERS-CoV operations room, previously identified since the emergence of the disease in the Kingdom, which operates 24 hours a day in order to receive reports of suspected [cases of MERS-CoV infection] in all health facilities, both public and private, in Jeddah;
- the MERS-CoV support operations room has 6 teams. Every team consists of a doctor, an epidemiology technician and technical nurse in order to communicate with the contacts of confirmed cases and perform the work of epidemiological investigations and the work of preventive measures for the contacts;
- full screening of [healthcare] workers at King Abdul Aziz Hospital and contacts. There were no positive cases of MERS-CoV infection identified as part of this screening;
- increasing the state of preparedness and awareness of all the preventive measures for MERS-CoV;
- communication with the population on the status of the patent in Ardhiya South and results of the tests on all contacts, which proved to be negative.

Since the appearance of a later suspected case in a healthcare worker at the King Fahd General Hospital in Jeddah, which was confirmed by the laboratory to be positive for MERS-CoV infection, the following measures were taken:
- a full scan of [healthcare] workers at King Fahd General in Jeddah. [This revealed there were 3 healthcare workers who were contacts of cases who had symptoms following care of cases, which means they are not the source of infection.];
- pressure on the King Fahad General Hospital has been relieved by referring Red Crescent cases to other hospitals, which provided an opportunity to take action of sterilization of the emergency department;
- a communication skills team coach has been assigned and is providing information about the disease, how it is spread and how to deal with the cases, in order to inform patients and their contacts on how to make them aware and to reduce the spread [of the MERS-CoV];
- information on the MERS-CoV disease and H1N1 flu has been disseminated at all health facilities, both public and private, including enhancing epidemiological surveillance for these diseases in order to raise awareness among health workers, especially emergency physicians to report suspected cases, with an emphasis on infection control procedures when dealing with all cases;
- daily reports on all confirmed cases and follow up on their health status are collected, as well as [reports on suspected cases] to the ministry;
- an epidemiological survey was made of all suspected cases, and nasal swabs were obtained and sent to the regional and laboratory with follow-up of results including test results on all contacts, and providing preventive measures for all contacts;
- has been ensuring the availability of sufficient quantities of prevention supplies to all hospitals and supporting hospitals Bmshat VTM [?] work on tests for the virus.

This brings the number of confirmed cases and previously announced in the governorate of Jeddah to 11, of whom 2 have died, 6 have recovered, and 3 are still receiving medical care.

Health Affairs in Jeddah stresses that these measures are in accordance with those sustained by His Royal Highness Prince Mishaal bin Abdullah bin Abdul Aziz Emir of Makkah Region, and His Royal Highness Prince Mishaal bin Majed bin Abdul Aziz, Governor of Jeddah, for all sectors to maintain all the possibilities to support prevention measures and follow His Highness and ministry officials to make sure that all procedures are implemented according to standards adopted by the World Health Organization, and also encourages the lack of rumors about any other injuries in hospitals in the ministry or incidence and mortality among other workers, and calls upon everyone to elicit information from the official website of the Ministry of Health (http://www.moh.gov.sa), which is updated with the number of cases where the virus has been confirmed and contains all the information and instructions and tips for dealing with the MERS-CoV.

