******
[4] UAE, 1 new case
Date: Tue 8 Apr 2014
Source: Arabian Business [edited]
http://www.arabianbusiness.com/abu-dhabi-confirms-new-case-of-mers-coronavirus-545677.html


Health chiefs in Abu Dhabi [United Arab Emirates] on Tuesday [8 Apr 2014] confirmed a new case of MERS-Coronavirus. Health Authority-Abu Dhabi (HAAD) said in a statement that a 59 year old male resident, known to have diabetes and final stage renal failure and currently on dialysis, complained of respiratory symptoms and was admitted and diagnosed with the illness.

HAAD also confirmed in the statement cited by news agency WAM that it is coordinating with the Ministry of Health [MoH] and other authorities in the country, and has taken all necessary measures as per international standards and recommendations from WHO.

WHO 1st issued an international alert regarding the disease in September 2012. Up to [1 Apr 2014], there have been 207 laboratory-confirmed cases of infection with MERS-CoV worldwide, including 87 deaths.

The MoH said that WHO has confirmed the virus is not a concern for public health at the moment, and that the current situation does not require a travel ban to any country in the world, screenings at different ports, or any restrictions on trade. The MoH confirmed that it is monitoring the situation closely.

[byline: Andy Sambidge]

--
communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Maintaining an accurate up to date count of laboratory-confirmed cases of MERS-CoV continues to be a challenge. The most recent global tally published by WHO on 1 Apr 2014 had a total count of 207 cases including 87 deaths. This tally did not include the 11 laboratory-confirmed cases including 2 deaths in Jeddah reported by the Saudi MOH website (see parts [2] and [3] above), and the case reported in Abu Dhabi, UAE, reported in the media report in [4] above. The addition of these 12 cases (including 2 deaths) will bring the global tally to 219 cases including 89 deaths. Clarification of these figures would be greatly appreciated.

According to the Saudi MOH website on MERS-CoV, there have been 175 laboratory-confirmed cases including 64 deaths in Saudi Arabia. A review of the media reports as well as the most recent report on the Saudi MOH website (see [2] and [3] above), there appears to be nosocomial transmission of the MERS-CoV in Jeddah, with a suggestion that the Emergency Department may have been the source of this spread. Many of the media reports (not included in this update, but readily available through web searching) suggest that the majority of the newly reported cases have been in healthcare workers and other hospital-based personnel. Clarification of this with information on possible exposure risks of these 11 confirmed cases in Jeddah would be greatly appreciated.

With respect to the media report on a newly reported laboratory-confirmed case of MERS-CoV in the UAE, this case represents the 18th such case reported with possible exposure in the UAE.

For a map of the region showing the UAE and Saudi Arabia, see https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=2390003,131. - Mod.MPP]
